 Hospitalization for bleeding peptic ulcers has declined over past decades [1].

 Bleeding from peptic ulcers however remains the commonest diagnosis in those who present with acute upper gastrointestinal bleeding (AUGIB).

 The incidence has been around 60-80/100,000 population.

 Endoscopic hemostatic therapy is the first treatment to those with active bleeding and major stigmata of bleeding.

 Endoscopic therapy stops bleeding and reduces rate of further bleeding, requirement for surgery and importantly deaths [2].

