 Despite of aggressive endoscopic therapy and maximal acid suppression using a PPI infusion, further bleeding occurs in around 8% of patients.

 Further bleeding is the single most important adverse prognostic factor and is associated with a 4 fold increase in mortality.

 From a National United Kingdom Audit on the management of patients with AUGIB, those who needed surgery for further bleeding and failed endoscopic control had a mortality of 28% [ 5 ].

 In addition to initial control of bleeding with endoscopic therapy, the prevention of further bleeding is an important objective.

 The use of routine second look endoscopy with re-treatment has been evaluated in several clinical trials.

